\f0\fs28 \cf0 Scrivener is also available for iOS so that you can write and structure while on your iPhone or iPad. The iOS version is available as a separate purchase from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://itunes.apple.com/app/scrivener/id972387337?ls=1&mt=8"}}{\fldrslt the App Store}}. Below we cover how to sync between platforms for those who also own the iOS version. If you don\'92t have Scrivener for iPhone or iPad, you can ignore this section.\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sl264\slmult1\sb300\sa120\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_H::1><$Scr_Ps::0>
\f2\b\fs36 Setting Up Dropbox on Your Mac\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_H::1><!$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0\fs28 You need to store any projects you wish to sync on Dropbox. You can get a free Dropbox account from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.getdropbox.com"}}{\fldrslt http://www.getdropbox.com}}. You\'92ll need to download the Dropbox app and install it on your Mac. Assuming you have Dropbox installed on your Mac:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Locate any Scrivener projects you want to sync in the Finder.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\li1440\fi-1440\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	
\f3 \uc0\u8259 
\f0 	}
\f1\fs24 \cf3 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f4\i\b Tip:
\f1\i0\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28  You can easily locate any project by opening it in Scrivener and then selecting 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f5\b File > Show Project in Finder
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f0\fs28  from the main menu.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	2.	}Ensure any projects you want to sync are closed. This is very important\'97if you leave any projects open in Scrivener while moving them into Dropbox, you could end up corrupting them and losing data.\
{\listtext	3.	}In the Finder, open another window (
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f5\b File > New Finder Window
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f0\fs28  in the Finder menu) and open your Dropbox folder in it (select \'93Dropbox\'94 in the Finder sidebar).\
{\listtext	4.	}Create a folder in which to store the projects you wish to sync with iOS. To sync, you must have a folder on Dropbox that you use only for sharing Scrivener projects between devices. The standard folder that the iOS version uses is /Apps/Scrivener, so if you want to use that, inside the Dropbox folder you would create a new folder named \'93Apps\'94 (if it doesn\'92t already exist) and then inside 
\f6\i that
\f0\i0  you would create a folder called \'93Scrivener\'94. However, you can create and use any folder you want for this, just as long as you only use it for storing Scrivener projects. (The reason you should only store Scrivener projects inside it is that everything in this folder will be synced to your iOS device, so anything else in the folder would take up unnecessary space on your device.)\
{\listtext	5.	}Move the projects you located in (1) into the folder you created in (4), for instance by dragging and dropping them.\
{\listtext	6.	}At this point, you can reopen the projects (e.g. by double-clicking on them in the Finder).\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 When creating a new project, if you want to sync it with iOS, be sure to save it into the Dropbox folder you created in (4) when asked where to choose a location for the new project. (If you don\'92t, you can still move it later using the steps above.)\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sl264\slmult1\sb300\sa120\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_H::1><$Scr_Ps::0>
\f2\b\fs36 Setting Up Dropbox on Your iPad or iPhone\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_H::1><!$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0\fs28 Next, open Scrivener on your iPhone and do the following:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Tap the \'93sync\'94 icon at the top of the projects screen and select 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f5\b Link Dropbox
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f0\fs28 . As long as you have an internet connection, this will bring up the Dropbox sign-in window, allowing you to sign in to your Dropbox account.\
{\listtext	2.	}Once you\'92ve signed in, you\'92ll be asked to choose a folder on Dropbox with which to sync your Scrivener projects. Be sure to choose the folder you set up in step (4) of \'93Setting Up Dropbox on Your Mac\'94.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\li1440\fi-1440\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	
\f3 \uc0\u8259 
\f0 	}
\f1\fs24 \cf3 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f4\i\b Note:
\f1\i0\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28  You can change this folder at any time by tapping \'93Edit\'94 in the nav bar at the top of the projects screen, then tapping the {\*\shppict{\pict {\*\nisusfilename ellipsis-circle}\picw16\pich16\picwgoal240\pichgoal240\pngblip }} / {\*\shppict{\pict {\*\nisusfilename gear-icon}\picw16\pich16\picwgoal240\pichgoal240\pngblip }} icon (depending on macOS version) in the footer bar that appears and selecting 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f5\b Dropbox Settings
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f0\fs28 .\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	3.	}Once you\'92ve chosen a folder, Scrivener will sync with Dropbox, downloading any files you have placed in your shared Dropbox folder. Projects stored on Dropbox will appear in their own section at the top of the projects list.\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 When you create a new project on iOS, you will be asked where to save it. If you choose to save it to Dropbox, after you sync, it will automatically appear in the Dropbox folder you created on your Mac, so that you can open the project there, too.\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sl264\slmult1\sb300\sa120\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_H::1><$Scr_Ps::0>
\f2\b\fs36 Making Changes to Projects\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_H::1><!$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0\fs28 Now that you have your project on both your Mac and iOS device, you need to make sure it is synced between devices whenever you make changes. Here\'92s how:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}On macOS, the Dropbox app you downloaded from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dropbox.com"}}{\fldrslt dropbox.com}} is always running in the background. Whenever a file is changed in the Dropbox folder, the Dropbox app automatically uploads it to the Dropbox servers. Whenever the Dropbox app detects new files on the Dropbox servers, it automatically downloads them to the Dropbox folder on your Mac. Whenever it is uploading or downloading files, it shows a \'93syncing\'94 badge in the Dropbox icon in the menu bar:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\li1440\fi-1440\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	
\f3 \uc0\u8259 
\f0 	}
\f1\fs24 {\*\shppict{\pict {\*\nisusfilename Skitch}\picw61\pich30\picwgoal1220\pichgoal600\pngblip }}
\f0\fs28 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	2.	}When you\'92ve finished editing on your Mac and want to open the project on iOS, it is 
\f6\i very
\f0\i0  important that you wait for the \'93syncing\'94 badge to disappear from the Dropbox icon in the Mac menu bar. Only when it disappears have all the files uploaded to the Dropbox servers. Until then, there is no way for the iOS version to download all of your changes, so if you don\'92t wait, you could end up with an incomplete sync and files missing from your project.\
{\listtext	3.	}Once you\'92re sure Dropbox has finished syncing on your Mac, on your iOS device, open Scrivener and tap the \'93sync\'94 icon in the nav bar of the projects screen. A progress bar will appear while the updated files download.\
{\listtext	4.	}Once the sync has finished, you are ready to open and edit the project on your iOS device.\
{\listtext	5.	}When you\'92ve finished making edits on iOS, tap the \'93sync\'94 icon once again in the projects screen. (The sync icon is also available in the nav bar while editing documents inside a project, and in the share button in the footer bar of the editor.) Once again, a progress bar will appear, this time to indicate that your changed files are being uploaded to the Dropbox servers. Wait for the sync to complete.\
{\listtext	6.	}When you return to your Mac, if the project is still open, a message should appear telling you that changes have been made and asking if you want to sync them. Before clicking to start the sync, though, make sure that the Dropbox app has finished downloading all the changed files. As you did before syncing on iOS, check the Dropbox icon in the menu bar on your Mac and do not tell Scrivener to sync the changes until the \'93syncing\'94 badge has disappeared. Once you are sure Dropbox has finished syncing, tell Scrivener to sync the changes. The project will close and reopen automatically, now with all the changes you made on iOS in place.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\li1440\fi-1440\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	
\f3 \uc0\u8259 
\f0 	}If you don\'92t see a message telling you that there are changes, you can go to 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f5\b File > Sync > with Mobile Devices
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f0\fs28  to force Scrivener to look for changes.\
{\listtext	
\f3 \uc0\u8259 
\f0 	}If the project was closed, only reopen it when you are sure Dropbox has finished syncing. When you open the project, all of the changes you made on iOS will be there.\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sl264\slmult1\sb300\sa120\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_H::1><$Scr_Ps::0>
\f2\b\fs36 Resolving Sync Problems\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_H::1><!$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0\fs28 If your iOS device tells you that a project you downloaded from your Mac seems to be invalid, it is most likely because you didn\'92t let Dropbox on macOS finish syncing all files before you downloaded them to iOS. To solve this issue, ensure the Dropbox app has finished syncing on your Mac, and then tap \'93sync\'94 again on iOS to download the rest of the files.\
Try not to edit a project on both devices without syncing, as this can lead to conflicts. For instance, suppose you make some changes on iOS, and then return to your Mac and make some changes to the project without first tapping \'93sync\'94 in iOS and waiting for Dropbox to download the changes to your Mac. In this case, conflicts will arise. Scrivener will do its best to resolve such conflicts, but it\'92s always better to try to avoid this happening.\
}